## A group of individuals of the same species



## Demography

> [!Population dynamics]+
> General study of population changes

> [!Demography]+
> The statistical study of populations, including:
> - birth rates
> - death rates
> - growth rates
> - age structures

- The statistical study of populations and how they change over time
	- Density
		- Number of individuals per unit area
		- Count individuals in an area and extrapolate that data
			- Can also count indirect indicators, such as nests and burrows
	- Size
		- Extrapolated from density
	- Distribution (Dispersion)
		- The spatial arrangement of organisms in an area
		- Types
			- Clumped
				- Organisms are clustered around eachother, or resources
				- Can be uniform or random within clumps
			- Uniform
				- Evenly dispersed
					- Caused by particular species interactions
					- IE predator territory, plants which release growth inhibitors
			- Random
			- ![Pasted image 20220906195107.png|200](data:image/png;base64,)
		- Different levels of organization are visible at different scales
			- IE within clumps organisms can be uniform, random, or further clumped
		- Human populations, like those of other animals and plants, are often studied this way
- Growth / Change in size
	- Rate of growth r = (births-deaths)+(immigrants-emigrants)
		- Natality - births
		- Mortality - death
		- Immigration
		- Emigration


## Exponential growth
- Populations with unlimited resources (such as when the population is very small), will grow exponentially
- Eventually hits the **carrying capacity** (k) of their ecosystem
	- Shifts exponential growth patterns into logistic growth patterns
	- Factors in carrying capacity
		- **Density-dependent factors**
			- Resource availability
				- Food, water, nutrients, etc
			- Buildup of toxins
			- Limited nesting sites
			- Disease
			- Predators/parasites
		- **Density-independent factors**
			- Temperature extremes
			- Extreme weather events
				- Hurricane, landslide, early frost 
			- Random chance events
			- *Can create sharp changes in the population over time, unlike density-dependent factors* 
	- Results in an S-shaped curve: Exponential growth gives way to logistic growth

## Biotic potential
- Rate at which a species is able to produce offspring
	- Varies based on environment
- **Low** biotic potential
	- **K-selected**
	- Takes a long time to reach carrying capacity even with good conditions
	- Factors
		- Large size
		- Slow development
		- Long-lived
		- Reproduce later in life
		- Few but large offspring
		- High parental care for offspring
- **High** biotic potential
	- **r-selected**
	- Can reach carrying capacity very rapidly if conditions are good
	- Factors
		- Smaller size
		- Fast development
		- Short-lived
		- Reproduction early in life
		- Many small offspring
		- Less parental care for offspring
